summary: Hello I have a bit of a question I recently started my journey with my best friend and partner Steven and he's a Gible and I've...
question: Hello I have a bit of a question I recently started my journey with my best friend and partner Steven and he's a Gible and I've noticed that his dragon type moves aren't working very often as they used to. Usually he's able to use dragon rage or dragon claw with no issues but recently they've taken longer to use and sometimes nothing happens at all I'm not sure if this is a sickness or something else but I do hope he's ok I really do love the little guy. Hope you can help and thanks in advance.
answer:
That is a strange situation. I’ve heard of Gible having difficulty executing higher level moves, but not usually having a rougher time with them when they usually did so well.

I can think of a few possibilities, but without being there they’re just shots in the dark. It’s possible that it’s sick, but it would be a rare and strange illness if it’s only affecting the dragon-type moves. It could possibly also be cold, as all dragon-types get sluggish in colder climates. It could be injured somewhere, and you just haven’t noticed. Take a closer look a the little Pokemon and check. And, as the biggest shot in the dark, it may have also found a rare item that’s causing this that hadn’t been discovered before. That’s the absolute least likely though.

I hope something here ends up being right. Good luck

summary: After the initial explosion, my ears were ringing and my head was disorientated. Around me, people were running out of the room....
caption:
After the initial explosion, my ears were ringing and my head was disorientated. Around me, people were running out of the room. Cables and embers fell from the ceiling and I could feel shards of glass crunch beneath my feet.
My hearing slowly returned as my ears filled with alarms and people screaming. A few fires had started across the room as I pulled my eyes to the incubation tube… It had shattered… Amniotic gel dripped from its tight fur and condensation billowed from its skin. Its eyes scanned the room with heavy jagged breaths.
Psychic energy rippled from its body, warping my vision like a heat wave. It slowly lifted one arm and power built in the air around its three-clawed fist. With a sharp motion, its hand snapped open and a pulse tore through the room, desks crunching in half, computer screens warping and in the distance, the sounds of new screams…
We had created a monster… we had created a god.

—————-

Here is my 180k celebration image! Hope you like it! I’m super unwell atm, so work is slow, but I didn’t wanna waste my time.
Bit of a closer look at Mewtwo here, wanted to make it look more like a real predator, an ultimate alpha but still keep its creepy clone aesthetic. It might not be what I finally settle on for Mewtwo but I still really like this one 🙂

Sadly, things are a bit slow at the moment, my Patreon support isn’t at its best and the more support I get, the more time I can spend on the project rather than freelance work 😊. If you can help on Patreon, I’d really appreciate it, plus I can get some more epic Pokemon images out for you! 😁 If you haven’t checked it out already, take a look at my Etsy store for cool merch! 🙂

Link in my bio 😉

tags: I'm really glad I didn't had to grind in Victory Road
Cue the rant from last time
She could have had some more variety in her team tho
Gengar and Misdreavus to be specific
But I guess wasting the players PP was a better tactic
summary: On to the next challenge. Phoebe, the Ghost Pokémon trainer. There aren't many ghosts, but Agatha in Kanto was also labeled...
body:
On to the next challenge. Phoebe, the Ghost Pokémon trainer. There aren’t many ghosts, but Agatha in Kanto was also labeled Ghost trainer, so…

What I expected was a long fight, which I eventually would win, what I thought inevitable.

But it came in other ways. Her team consists of three Pokémon, two of which are there double. She starts off with a Dusclops. It exerts its Pressure.

That will not be fun. It means that I use double as much PP as moves.

And it starts with Protect. And then another Protect. And then another. What. Why is this ugly ghost able to use that move three times successfully in a row? I just wasted 6 PP for nothing. As if I wasn’t pissed off about that from the training in Victory Road.

Then it starts using Shadow Punch. And I just… I hadn’t had anything against that. Every single one of my Pokémon were unable to get far in this fight.

I eventually knocked the first Dusclops out, but lo and behold, out came a second. At a higher level. With the stronger Shadow Ball. It also was faster than my Medicham, so that didn’t help me.

The battle was lost. I lost the league challenge.

What to do now? Retire as one of the few trainers to beat all of the gym leaders? As trainer who reached stage two of the league? And by the way saved all of the region from simultaneously drowning and burning.

Advance to the next region and try my luck in Sinnoh? Tuck in the tail and abscond this region?

Not just no, hell no. I’m not one to give up that easily. One lost match doesn’t mean anything.

It only meant, I had to grind. In Victory Road. Ugh, I’m already frustrated.

But wait. I made it to stage 2, didn’t I. That means, I can defeat stage 1, meaning Sidney.

I can train my Pokémon on the motherloving Elite Four. Well, one of them at least.

And that I did. I ran through him quite some times, never using any items in battle or after.

Once I got all my Pokémon around level 45 (the level on which I defeated Red in the last installment, mind you), I tried again.

I beat Sidney one last time, then healed my team and advanced towards Phoebe.

She used the same tactics as before. But I didn’t.

I started with Ezri. Used Calm Mind about three or four times. Same with Double Team. Had to heal her, cause the Dusclops started getting antsy and used Shadow Punch. Only this time she was strong enough to withstand.

Psychic got rid of the first Dusclops and Banette. Then came Sableye. Another dark type. I’m surprised that Sidney hadn’t had one of those.

But, Ezri not only knows Psychic, Calm Mind and Double Team. She also knows Magical Leaf Thunderbolt. Which, at +3 or +4 was enough to oneshot Sableye.

She had another Dusclops and Banette, but…

Don’t ever let a Gardevoir set up on you with Calm Mind. It’s devastating. But this time, much to my pleasure.

I learned. I shouldn’t take my team’s successes for granted. I still need to devise tactics and successfully employ them.

With this said, I’m advancing to stage 3 now.

Once I got all my Pokémon around level 45 (the level on which I defeated Red in the last installment, mind you), I tried again.

I beat Sidney one last time, then healed my team and advanced towards Phoebe.

She used the same tactics as before. But I didn’t.

I started with Ezri. Used Calm Mind about three or four times. Same with Double Team. Had to heal her, cause the Dusclops started getting antsy and used Shadow Punch. Only this time she was strong enough to withstand.

Psychic got rid of the first Dusclops and Banette. Then came Sableye. Another dark type. I’m surprised that Sidney hadn’t had one of those.

But, Ezri not only knows Psychic, Calm Mind and Double Team. She also knows Magical Leaf Thunderbolt. Which, at +3 or +4 was enough to oneshot Sableye.

She had another Dusclops and Banette, but…

Don’t ever let a Gardevoir set up on you with Calm Mind. It’s devastating. But this time, much to my pleasure.

I learned. I shouldn’t take my team’s successes for granted. I still need to devise tactics and successfully employ them.

With this said, I’m advancing to stage 3 now.
